[normal] 
[normal]See blog, A view of science worth reflec
[normal]ting on, 16/11, wattsupwiththat and Wikipedia cargo cult science.  Feynman commented:-
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“
[normal]In the 
[normal]South Seas
[normal] there is a cargo cult of people. During the war they saw airplanes land with lots of good materials, and they want the same thing to happen now. So they've arranged to imitate things like runways, to put fires along the sides of the runways, to make a wooden hut for a man to sit in, with two wooden pieces on his head like headphones and bars of bamboo sticking out like antennas--he's the controller--and they wait for the airplanes to land. They're doing everything right. The form is perfect. It looks exactly the way it looked before. But it doesn't work. No airplanes land. So I call these things cargo cult science, because they follow all the apparent precepts and forms of scientific investigation, but they're missing something essential, because the planes don't land.
[normal]”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Feynman cautioned that to avoid becoming cargo cult scientists, researchers must avoid fooling themselves, be willing to question and doubt
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]their own theories and their own results, and investigate possible flaws in a theory or an experiment. He recommended that researchers adopt an unusually high level of honesty
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]which is rarely encountered in everyday life
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]At a more modest scale, but apparently using similar models, the Met Office mis-forecast a “barbecue summer” for the washout in 2009; “milder-than-average winter” for 2010/11 through which we shivered; and a “drier-than-average” spring and early summer just before one of the wettest summers on record. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]“Global Warming: How to approach the science”, HoC, February 2012, 
[normal]http://scienceandpublicpolicy.org/images/stories/papers/reprint/how_to_approach_the_science.pdf
